    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so like, who is this \"neutral third party\" usually? is it just a bank or a lawyer or something? and does the money just sit there doing nothing until the closing date?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"neutral third party\" in the context of an escrow account for a house purchase is typically an escrow company, which can be a specialized real estate firm, a bank, or an attorney's office. They do much more than just holding the money; they also act as the record keeper for all the documents and information related to the transaction.\n\nYes, the money can sit in the escrow account until the closing date, but it's not truly \"doing nothing.\" The escrow company ensures that all the conditions and contingencies of your purchase agreement are met. This includes verifying the property's title, ensuring that the home inspection doesn't reveal any major issues, and confirming that you have the necessary funds to proceed. Only once these conditions are satisfied will the escrow company release the funds and documents to the appropriate parties, enabling the successful closing of the home sale.",
