    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if the escrow company is the one holding all the cash and the important papers, does that mean they basically have total control over it? like, what's to stop things from getting messy if there's a dispute between the buyer and seller? is there like a specific way they manage the \"guarding\" of the assets to make sure nothing goes wrong?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the escrow company holds the funds and documents, they don't have \"total control\" over them. Their role is to act as an impartial guardian of the assets, ensuring that the terms of the purchase agreement are adhered to. In the event of a dispute between the buyer and the seller, the escrow company may serve as an arbitrator or facilitate communication to resolve the issue. They often have established procedures and legal agreements in place to manage such disputes and protect the assets involved.\n\nEscrow companies are bound by law to follow the instructions of the escrow agreement, which both buyer and seller have signed. This agreement outlines the conditions that must be met before the funds and documents are released. In addition, escrow companies are typically insured and regulated to ensure that they operate in a professional and trustworthy manner. This level of oversight helps to prevent any \"messy\" situations and ensure that the assets are safeguarded throughout the transaction.",
      "source": "target",
